Johnnie Walker is selected as a brand for analysis. Johnnie Walker is a brand of Scotch whisky (now owned by Diageo) that originated in the Scottish town of Kilmarnock, East Ayrshire. The brand was first established by grocer John Walker. It is the most widely distributed brand of blended Scotch whisky in the world, sold in almost every country.

The csv file (JW_Tweets.csv) downloaded in the specified path is attached in portal. CSV file contains 1308 tweets for period 5-May-2019 to 14-May-2019. The twees are downloaded from twitter as a csv file with name JW_Tweets.csv. This file is used for analysis.

Clean the tweets in text & statussource columns.

#Clean the tweets in text column
clean_tweets=tweets.df$text

#Convert the tweets in to lower case
clean_tweets = tolower(clean_tweets)

#Remove retweet entities
clean_tweets = gsub('RT @', '', clean_tweets)
clean_tweets = gsub('(RT|via)((?:\\b\\W*@\\w+)+)', '', clean_tweets)

#Remove at people
clean_tweets = gsub('@\\w+', '', clean_tweets)

#Remove punctuation
clean_tweets = gsub('[[:punct:]]', '', clean_tweets)

#Remove numbers
clean_tweets = gsub('[[:digit:]]', '', clean_tweets)

#Remove html links
clean_tweets = gsub('http\\w+', '', clean_tweets)

#Remove unnecessary spaces
clean_tweets = gsub('[ \t]{2,}', '', clean_tweets)
clean_tweets = gsub('^\\s+|\\s+$', '', clean_tweets)

#Remove emojis or special characters
clean_tweets = gsub('<.*>', '', enc2native(clean_tweets))

#Remove unnecessary spaces
clean_tweets <- str_replace_all(clean_tweets," "," ")

#Remove URLs
#clean_tweets <- str_replace_all(clean_tweets, "http://t.co/[a-z,A-Z,0-9]*{8}","")

#Remove retweet header, there is only one
clean_tweets <- str_replace(clean_tweets,"RT @[a-z,A-Z]*: ","")

#Remove hashtags
clean_tweets <- str_replace_all(clean_tweets,"#[a-z,A-Z]*","")

#Remove references to other screennames
clean_tweets <- str_replace_all(clean_tweets,"@[a-z,A-Z]*","")   

#Replace johnnie walker by single word
clean_tweets = gsub('johnnie walker', 'johnniewalker', clean_tweets)
clean_tweets = gsub('johnniewalker', '', clean_tweets)

#Replace white walker by single word
clean_tweets = gsub('white walker', 'whitewalker', clean_tweets)

#Push back the cleaned text to text column
tweets.df$text= clean_tweets
View(tweets.df)

#Clean the tweets in statusSource column
clean_tweets=tweets.df$statusSource
#clean_tweets = gsub('<.*>', '', enc2native(clean_tweets))
clean_tweets = gsub('<.*?>', '', clean_tweets)

clean_tweets = gsub('Twitter', '', clean_tweets)
clean_tweets = gsub('for', '', clean_tweets)
#Push back the cleaned text to statusSource column
tweets.df$statusSource= clean_tweets

#View data frame
View(tweets.df)

All that are not required and give trouble for analysis like URLs, extra spaces, stop words, etc. are removed using gsub which replaces specified string with provided string. The text is converted in to lower case for uniformity. Johnnie Walker is removed as it is not required to count the term for which we are doing all the analysis.

Build corpus for text mining.

#Create document corpus with tweet text
myCorpus<- Corpus(VectorSource(tweets.df$text))
myCorpus1<- Corpus(VectorSource(tweets.df$statusSource))

Do some more cleaning on the corpus and take a copy of corpus.

#Convert to Lowercase
myCorpus <- tm_map(myCorpus, content_transformer(stri_trans_tolower))
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(myCorpus,
## content_transformer(stri_trans_tolower)): transformation drops documents
#Remove the links (URLs)
removeURL <- function(x) gsub("http[^[:space:]]*", "", x)  
myCorpus <- tm_map(myCorpus, content_transformer(removeURL))
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(myCorpus, content_transformer(removeURL)):
## transformation drops documents
#Remove the @ (usernames)
removeUsername <- function(x) gsub("@[^[:space:]]*", "", x)  
myCorpus <- tm_map(myCorpus, content_transformer(removeUsername))
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(myCorpus, content_transformer(removeUsername)):
## transformation drops documents
#Remove anything except the english language and space
removeNumPunct <- function(x) gsub("[^[:alpha:][:space:]]*", "", x)   
myCorpus <- tm_map(myCorpus, content_transformer(removeNumPunct))
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(myCorpus, content_transformer(removeNumPunct)):
## transformation drops documents

All that are not required and give trouble for analysis like URLs, extra spaces, stop words, etc. are removed from corpus using tm_map which has many text cleaning functions. The text in corpus is converted in to lower case for uniformity.

Perform topic modelling on the tweets. Get 5 topics with 7 terms in each topic.

#Topic Modelling to identify latent/hidden topics using LDA technique
dtm <- as.DocumentTermMatrix(tdm)
rowTotals <- apply(dtm , 1, sum)
NullDocs <- dtm[rowTotals==0, ]
dtm   <- dtm[rowTotals> 0, ]

if (length(NullDocs$dimnames$Docs) > 0) {
  tweets.df <- tweets.df[-as.numeric(NullDocs$dimnames$Docs),]
}

#Find 5 topics with first 7 terms of every topic
lda <- LDA(dtm, k = 5) # find 5 topics
term <- terms(lda, 7) # first 7 terms of every topic
(term <- apply(term, MARGIN = 2, paste, collapse = ", "))
##                                                              Topic 1 
##              "whisky, plans, will, edition, house, got, whitewalker"

Perform sentiment analysis on tweets in the text column.

#Sentiment Analysis
#Understand emotional valence in tweets
mysentiment<-get_nrc_sentiment((tweets.df$text))

#Get sentiment score for each emotion
mysentiment.positive =sum(mysentiment$positive)
mysentiment.anger =sum(mysentiment$anger)
mysentiment.anticipation =sum(mysentiment$anticipation)
mysentiment.disgust =sum(mysentiment$disgust)
mysentiment.fear =sum(mysentiment$fear)
mysentiment.joy =sum(mysentiment$joy)
mysentiment.sadness =sum(mysentiment$sadness)
mysentiment.surprise =sum(mysentiment$surprise)
mysentiment.trust =sum(mysentiment$trust)
mysentiment.negative =sum(mysentiment$negative)

#Create the bar chart
yAxis <- c(mysentiment.positive,
           + mysentiment.anger,
           + mysentiment.anticipation,
           + mysentiment.disgust,
           + mysentiment.fear,
           + mysentiment.joy,
           + mysentiment.sadness,
           + mysentiment.surprise,
           + mysentiment.trust,
           + mysentiment.negative)

xAxis <- c("Positive","Anger","Anticipation","Disgust","Fear","Joy","Sadness",
           "Surprise","Trust","Negative")
colors <- c("green","red","blue","orange","red","green","orange","blue","green","red")
yRange <- range(0,yAxis)

#Plot twitter sentiments
barplot(yAxis, names.arg = xAxis, 
        xlab = "Emotional valence", ylab = "Score", main = "Twitter sentiment", 
        sub = "Johnnie Walker", col = colors, border = "black", xpd = F, ylim = yRange,
        axisnames = T, cex.axis = 0.8, cex.sub = 0.8, col.sub = "blue")

By observing the emotional valence scores graph, we can understand that Johnnie Walker brand has more positive sentiment & trust among people and is used in joyful moods. Anticipation also is more in the graph which indicates that people have more expectation on these brands products. Bars indicating negative feelings are very short when compared to the bars indicating positive sentiments. This shows that overall there is positive opinion for Johnnie Walker brand among people.

Understand polarities by observing movement of sentiment scores for the period in which the tweets are collected (5-May-2019 to 14-May-2019)

#Sentiment Analysis
#Plot by date - understanding cummulative sentiment score movement
mysentimentvalues <- data.frame(get_sentiment((tweets.df$text)))
colnames(mysentimentvalues)<-"polarity"
mysentimentvalues$date <- tweets.df$created
result <- aggregate(polarity ~ date, data = mysentimentvalues, sum)
result

When observing the polarity in order to understand the movement of sentiment scores from 5-May-2019 to 14-May-2019, we can see that polarity is very high in the middle around 9th may and somewhat on 13th may.

Conclusion

Overall Johnnie Walker, as a brand has positive sentiment among people. By analysis we can understand that people have lot of trust on this brand and use it for celebrating at parties when in joyful mood.
